(Rosenblatt, Greenberg, Solomon, Pyszczynski, & Lyon, 
1989). Given the basic premise that death awareness, or mor-
tality salience, can be paralyzing, TMT posits that humans 
have evolved psychological strategies—such as self-esteem 
(Pyszczynski, Greenberg, Solomon, Arndt, & Schimel, 
2004)—as defenses against the existential angst that thinking 
about their own mortality elicits. The bulk of TMT research 
has focused on positive self-evaluations as buffers against 
death-related anxiety. Studies indicate that during periods of 
mortality salience, individuals increase their adherence to cul-
tural values and worldviews in order to contribute to or play a 
part in something more enduring than the self (e.g., Gailliot, 
Stillman, Schmeichel, Plant, & Maner, 2008; Maheswaran & 
Agrawal, 2004).
Although terror management processes may be universal in 
the sense that they are designed to help people cope with mor-
tality salience, the specific techniques used to cope should 
nevertheless be culturally contingent. Though this has long 
been acknowledged by TMT theorists (Greenberg et al., 1990), 
few empirical studies have explored the nature and divergence 
of such coping processes across cultures.
The vast majority of TMT studies have focused on Euro-
